# small utility to clean up backup files:
def clean():
    print(subprocess.run("rm -f \#*; rm -fr bck.*",shell=True))
# small utility to run with mpiexec
def run_mpi(cmd,nprocs=1):
    return subprocess.run("mpiexec -np {} --oversubscribe {}".format(nprocs,cmd),shell=True)

Exercise 1

In this exercise we perform a replica-exchange umbrella sampling simulation. We do it using a single plumed.dat file in the parent directory. We then prepare four base names for the four simulations

  • start from A, without exchanges
  • start from B, without exchanges
  • start from A, with exchanges
  • start from B, with exchanges
In[7]:
at=np.linspace(-np.pi,np.pi,33)[:-1]
print(at)
for start in "A","B":
    for exchanges in "","x":
        with open("plumed_us_{}.dat".format(start+exchanges),"w") as f:
            print("""
        # vim:ft=plumed
        # since simulation run in subdir, we refer to a file in the parent dir:
        MOLINFO STRUCTURE=../reference.pdb 
        phi: TORSION ATOMS=@phi-2 
        psi: TORSION ATOMS=@psi-2
        bb: RESTRAINT ARG=phi KAPPA=200.0 AT=@replicas:{}
        # I am here writing files in the parent directory
        PRINT ARG=phi,psi,bb.bias FILE=../colvar_us_{}.dat STRIDE=100
        """.format(','.join(str(a) for a in at),start+exchanges),file=f)
        for i in range(len(at)):
            dd="us_"+start+exchanges+"_"+str(i)
            # we here copy the relevant files in the subdir
            subprocess.run("rm -fr {} && mkdir {} && \
                            cp topol{}.tpr {}/topol.tpr".format(dd,dd,start,dd),shell=True)

In[13]:
def analyze(traj):
    kb=0.008314462618
    T=300
    bias=np.zeros((len(traj[0]["bb.bias"]),32))
    for i in range(32):
        bias[:,i]=traj[i]["bb.bias"]
    w=wham.wham(bias,T=kb*T)
    tr=traj[0].phi[-len(bias):]
    is_in_B=np.int_(np.logical_and(tr>0,tr<2))
    is_in_A=np.int_(tr<0)
    return np.average(is_in_B,weights=np.exp(w["logW"]))/np.average(is_in_A,weights=np.exp(w["logW"]))
print("relative population (A)               :",analyze(colvar_A))
print("relative population (A with exchanges):",analyze(colvar_Ax))
print("relative population (B)               :",analyze(colvar_B))
print("relative population (B with exchanges):",analyze(colvar_Bx))

relative population (A)               : 0.0035809326113286676
relative population (A with exchanges): 0.030813059866354995
relative population (B)               : 0.015909491115979803
relative population (B with exchanges): 0.02381113120031632

When not doing exchanges, the dependence of the result on the initial state is large. When doing exchanges, dependence is less.

Note that some replicas are diffusing whereas others are stuck. In general, you should not expect that every replica diffuses on the whole range (in the same way as you should not expect that if you cut your plain MD simulation in 32 consecutive block each block is identical to the others). However, you should expect several replicas spannning a significant range.

Also notice that replicas with the 3 highest indexes are kind of separated from the others. In line of principle, for this system one should propose also exchanges between first and last replica. This would probably make these replicas join those with low indexes.

In[20]:
# Finally use bootstrap with 32 blocks
# This will take a while
kb=0.008314462618
T=300
for start in "A","B":
    if start=="A":
        replica_temp=replica_tempA
    else:
        replica_temp=replica_tempB
    bias=np.zeros((2001*32,32))
    for i in range(32):
        col=plumed.read_as_pandas("colvar_us_process_{}x.{}.dat".format(start,i))
        bias[:,i]=col["bb.bias"]
    w0=wham.wham(bias,T=kb*T)
    tr=col.phi
    is_in_B=np.int_(np.logical_and(tr>0,tr<2))
    is_in_A=np.int_(tr<0)
    print("Whole trajectory:",np.average(is_in_B,weights=np.exp(w0["logW"]))/np.average(is_in_A,weights=np.exp(w0["logW"])))

    pop=[]
    for i in range(200):
        c=np.random.choice(32,32)
        tr_w=np.zeros(32)
        for k in range(32):
            tr_w+=np.bincount(np.int_(replica_temp)[:,c[k]+1],minlength=32)
        w=wham.wham(bias.reshape((32,-1,32))[c].reshape((-1,32)),T=kb*T,traj_weight=tr_w)
        tr=np.array(col.phi).reshape((32,-1))[c].flatten()
        is_in_B=np.int_(np.logical_and(tr>0,tr<2))
        is_in_A=np.int_(tr<0)
        pop.append(np.average(is_in_B,weights=np.exp(w["logW"]))/np.average(is_in_A,weights=np.exp(w["logW"])))
        print("  iteration ",i,pop[-1])
    print("Bootstrap",np.average(pop),np.std(pop))

    plt.xlabel("$\phi$")

    plt.ylim((-np.pi,+np.pi))
    plt.title(title)

Now all replicas can sample all minima, but with different populations. Clearly, transitions only happened in replica zero (the other replicas do not cross the transition state). The "neutral" replica was able to sample both states. This is happening since the less stable state is not too high in free energy. The replica biasing $\psi$ didn't sample very much the region at $\psi \approx -1$ and $\phi<0$. This is because this barrier was hidden by the metastable state at $\phi>0$. This didn't happen in the simulation without exchanges, because this latter state was not visited. Finally, notice that the simulation biasing $\phi$ did not differ much from the corresponding simulation without exchanges. This is because the other variable ($\psi$) was not of much help here. In more complicated cases, you can expect more than one replica to cooperatively help each other.

In[34]:
def analyze(traj):
    kb=0.008314462618
    T=300
    bias=np.zeros((len(traj[0]["m.bias"]),3))
    for i in range(3):
        bias[:,i]=traj[i]["m.bias"]
    w=wham.wham(bias,T=kb*T)
    tr=traj[0].phi[-len(bias):]
    is_in_B=np.int_(np.logical_and(tr>0,tr<2))
    is_in_A=np.int_(tr<0)
    return np.average(is_in_B,weights=np.exp(w["logW"]))/np.average(is_in_A,weights=np.exp(w["logW"]))
print("relative population (no exchanges)  :",analyze(be))
print("relative population (with exchanges):",analyze(bex))

relative population (no exchanges)  : 0.0009558562194537331
relative population (with exchanges): 0.025324473263561294

Note: the apparent population of the second state when NOT doing exchanges is much lower. The reason is that replicas 1 and 2, based on their bias potentials, were supposed to be able to go there. However, they didn't. This is a general issue when using WHAM: each of the replicas should have sampled all the relevant states (with that Hamiltonian). Clearly, exchanges help all replicas provided that at least one replica can cross each of the relevant barriers.

In[35]:
import numpy as np
import re
T=np.geomspace(300,800,4)
for i in range(len(T)):
    with open("top/grompp.mdp") as f:
        l=f.read()
    with open("top/grompp{}.mdp".format(i),"w") as f:
        # if you use this script on your input files, make sure that 300 only appears
        # on the temperature line! or better replace it with a placeholder string such as __TEMP__
        print(re.sub("300",str(T[i]),l),file=f)
    subprocess.run("mkdir -p ptmetad_{}".format(i),shell=True)
    subprocess.run("mkdir -p pt_{}".format(i),shell=True)
    # we will initialize some replica in A and some replica in B
    if i%2==0:
        conf="A"
    else:
        conf="B"
    # we use -maxwarn 1 here since the grompp file has been adapted from an old gromacs version.
    # in general, only use this option after you have understood that the warning is harmless
    subprocess.run("cd top/; gmx_mpi grompp -f grompp{}.mdp -c conf{}.gro -maxwarn 1 -o ../ptmetad_{}/topol.tpr".format(i,conf,i), shell=True)
    subprocess.run("cd top/; gmx_mpi grompp -f grompp{}.mdp -c conf{}.gro -maxwarn 1 -o ../pt_{}/topol.tpr".format(i,conf,i), shell=True)

is_in_B=np.int_(np.logical_and(tr>0,tr<2))
is_in_A=np.int_(tr<0)
print("relative population:",np.average(is_in_B)/np.average(is_in_A))
# state B is visited much more than in pt

In[47]:
# population from ptmetad WITH REWEIGHTING
# this is expected to be correct
tr=colvar_ptmetad.phi[:]
is_in_B=np.int_(np.logical_and(tr>0,tr<2))
is_in_A=np.int_(tr<0)
logW=+colvar_ptmetad["m.bias"]
logW-=np.max(logW)
logW/=kb*300
print("relative population:",np.average(is_in_B,weights=np.exp(logW))/np.average(is_in_A,weights=np.exp(logW)))

relative population: 0.014875271518731829

The latter case shows that if you have a variable that distinguishes approximately the metastable state but does not single out the transition state (such as $\psi$) it can be convenient to flatten its histogram in a PTMETAD simulation so as to have more sampling also in the less stable state. Having a more uniform simulated population of the two states will make the statistical error on their unbiased population smaller.

import numpy as np
import re
T=np.geomspace(300,310,4)
for i in range(len(T)):
    with open("top/grompp.mdp") as f:
        l=f.read()
    with open("top/grompp{}.mdp".format(i),"w") as f:
        # if you use this script on your input files, make sure that 300 only appears
        # on the temperature line! or better replace it with a placeholder string such as __TEMP__
        print(re.sub("300",str(T[i]),l),file=f)
    subprocess.run("mkdir -p ptmetad310_{}".format(i),shell=True)
    # we will initialize some replica in A and some replica in B
    if i%2==0:
        conf="A"
    else:
        conf="B"
    # we use -maxwarn 1 here since the grompp file has been adapted from an old gromacs version.
    # in general, only use this option after you have understood that the warning is harmless
    subprocess.run("cd top/; gmx_mpi grompp -f grompp{}.mdp -c conf{}.gro -maxwarn 1 -o ../ptmetad310_{}/topol.tpr".format(i,conf,i), shell=True)
